      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Rent control in New York, rather than a boon for elderly tenants, may be in practice a mixed curse (letter, June 10).</p>
        <p>Rent control effectively reduces the options of the elderly of limited income. The perceived benefit of below-market rent lends the rent-controlled apartment a disproportionate psychological importance. It becomes too risky to consider moving, even if it might objectively mean much improved living conditions.</p>
        <p>I have seen older relatives in my own family who were afraid to give up a large rent-controlled apartment in a dangerous neighborhood for a smaller one (at market rent) in a better environment. The rent-controlled apartment takes on a value far beyond its actual worth, and keeps the elderly in substandard living conditions long past the time they should have moved.</p>
        <p>EILEEN POLLOCK  New York, June 10, 2000</p>
      </block>
